.TH HELLO 1 "" "" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
hello \- print a greeting message
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hello
.RI [ OPTIONS ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hello
is a minimal command-line program that prints a greeting message to standard
output and exits.
.PP
The sources were recovered from the
.I hello-gcc-O2
build artifact, originally compiled from C++ with GCC at optimization level
.BR -O2 .
The program is structured around a small entry point
.RB ( src/main.cpp )
that delegates to a greeting helper
.RB ( src/print_message.cpp )
which is responsible for emitting the message text.
.PP
.B hello
takes no required arguments and produces no output other than the greeting.
.SH OPTIONS
.B hello
does not document any command-line options beyond those implied by its
.I [OPTIONS]
synopsis. Invoking the program with no arguments prints the greeting and
exits successfully.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR cmake (1),
.BR gcc (1),
.BR g++ (1)
